Now, when it was proved that there was nothing more in question than unreflecting and womanly compassion for the unfortunate, and that there was no trace of deliber- ate malice, they were indeed exempted from the penalty of death, but nevertheless condemned to exile. 26th July, 1698).- After dinner to-day the Lord Envoy, with the greater part of his suite, went to Prince Galizin’s, as well to pay him a ceremonial visit as to enjoy the freedom of familiar discourse with him.

With strange politeness he commanded his musi- cians, who are natives of Poland, to play various airs for the amusement of the company, and earn- estly begged the Lord Envoy to come to his country house, where he purposed to take the Lord Arch- bishop for his amusement, before he should finally start for Persia. He ordered a great variety of wines to be served to display the extent of his opu- lenoe.
